\begin_body

\begin_layout Subsection*
Solve for global min var portfolio
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Begin with portfolio covariance 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 and returns z.
 The global minimum variance portfolio is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\min & w'\Sigma w\\
s.t.1'w= & 1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the last term imposes a unique solution w/o loss of generality.
 Then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0= & \Sigma w_{g}-\lambda1\\
w_{g}= & \lambda\Sigma^{-1}1\\
1= & \lambda1'\Sigma^{-1}1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=1'\Sigma^{-1}1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{g}=\frac{\Sigma^{-1}1}{A}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Proof that 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{p}\Sigma w_{g}=\frac{1}{A}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pick any portfolio s.t.
 wlog 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{p}'1=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
w_{g}= & \frac{\Sigma^{-1}1}{A}\\
w_{p}\Sigma w_{g}= & \frac{w_{p}'1}{A}=\frac{1}{A}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Thoughts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Potential Issue: Uniform Returns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The weight vector is not observed, and neither is the covariance matrix.
 Suppose we regress 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{p}$
\end_inset

 on the minimum variance portfolio.
 Then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E\left[R_{P}|R_{G}\right]= & E\left[R_{P}\right]+\frac{w_{p}\Sigma w_{g}}{\sigma_{G}^{2}}\left(E\left[R_{G}\right]-E\left[R_{P}\right]\right)\\
= & E\left[R_{G}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the expected return of the portfolio is just the return on the minimum
 variance portfolio, and the beta of the portfolio to any other portfolio
 of the same weights is 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Interestingly, this implies the beta of any stock to the minimum variance
 portfolio is 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Resolution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand what is going on, return to the original problem with no rfr:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\min & w'\Sigma w\\
s.t.w'1= & 1\\
w'z= & \mu
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Lagrangian is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
L= & w'\Sigma w+\gamma\left(r-w'z\right)+\lambda\left(1-w'1\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
FOC:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Sigma w= & \gamma z+\lambda1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $A=1'\Sigma^{-1}1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B\equiv1'\Sigma^{-1}z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C=z'\Sigma^{-1}z$
\end_inset

.
 Then plug in the constraints:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
1= & \gamma B+\lambda A\\
\mu= & \gamma C+\lambda B
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda= & \frac{1-\gamma B}{A}\\
\mu= & \gamma C+B\left[\frac{1-\gamma B}{A}\right]\\
\gamma= & \frac{\mu A-B}{AC-B^{2}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\gamma= & \frac{1-\lambda A}{B}\\
\mu= & \frac{C-\lambda AC}{B}+\lambda B\\
\lambda= & \frac{\mu B-C}{B^{2}-AC}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use Black's result that the convex combo of MV portfolios is MV.
 Solve for the global minimum variance portfolio:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
w_{G}\equiv arg\min_{w} & \gamma\mu_{G}+\lambda\\
FOC:\\
0= & \frac{2A\mu_{G}-B}{AC-B^{2}}+\frac{B}{B^{2}-AC}\\
\mu_{G}= & \frac{B}{A}\\
\lambda_{G}= & \frac{1}{A},\;\gamma_{G}=0\\
w_{G}= & \frac{\Sigma^{-1}1}{A}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Need a distinct portfolio:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu_{D}= & \frac{C}{B}\\
\gamma_{D}= & \frac{1}{B},\;\lambda_{D}=0\\
w_{D}= & \frac{\Sigma^{-1}z}{B}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define a convex combination:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
w_{a}= & \left(1-a\right)\frac{\Sigma^{-1}1}{A}+a\frac{\Sigma^{-1}z}{B}\\
\sigma_{a}\equiv\Sigma w_{a}= & \frac{1-a}{A}1+\frac{a}{B}z\\
\sigma_{a}^{2}\equiv w'_{a}\sigma_{a}= & \frac{1-a}{A}+\frac{a}{B}z_{a}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let p be any portfolio.
 Then solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1-a}{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a}{B}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{ap}\equiv w_{p}\sigma_{a}= & \frac{1-a}{A}+\frac{a}{B}z_{p}\\
\frac{a}{B}= & \frac{\sigma_{a}^{2}-\sigma_{ap}}{z_{a}-z_{p}}\\
\frac{1-a}{A}= & \sigma_{a}^{2}-\left[\frac{\sigma_{a}^{2}-\sigma_{ap}}{z_{a}-z_{p}}\right]z_{a}\\
= & \frac{\sigma_{ap}z_{a}-\sigma_{a}^{2}z_{p}}{z_{a}-z_{p}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plug in:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{a}{B}z= & \sigma_{a}-\frac{1-a}{A}1\\
z= & \left[\sigma_{a}-\frac{\sigma_{ap}z_{a}-\sigma_{a}^{2}z_{p}}{z_{a}-z_{p}}1\right]\frac{z_{a}-z_{p}}{\sigma_{a}^{2}-\sigma_{ap}}\\
= & \frac{z_{a}-z_{p}}{\sigma_{a}^{2}-\sigma_{ap}}\sigma_{a}-\frac{\sigma_{ap}z_{a}-\sigma_{a}^{2}z_{p}}{\sigma_{a}^{2}-\sigma_{ap}}1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pick 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{ap}$
\end_inset

 that is orthogonal:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
z= & \frac{\sigma_{a}}{\sigma_{a}^{2}}\left(z_{a}-z_{p}\right)+z_{p}1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus we have the capm, since for any portfolio i:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
z_{i}= & \beta_{ai}\left(z_{a}-z_{p}\right)+z_{p}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now the market portfolio is not unique.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

 (is a GMV).
 Then the previous solution fails, as we can't plug in for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{a}$
\end_inset

 to get the CAPM: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{a}^{2}= & \sigma_{ap}=\frac{1}{A}\\
\frac{a}{B}= & 0\\
\frac{1-a}{A}= & 1\\
0= & \sigma_{a}-\left[\frac{\sigma_{ap}z_{a}-\sigma_{a}^{2}z_{p}}{z_{a}-z_{p}}\right]1\\
0= & 0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Could we still have a valid discount factor? I doubt it.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
z_{a}=\\
1= & EMz_{i}\\
1= & cov\left(M,z\right)+E\left[M\right]E\left[z_{i}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
cov\left(M,z\right) & =w_{i}'\Sigma w_{G}\\
 & =\frac{w_{i}\Sigma\Sigma^{-1}1}{A}\\
 & =\frac{1}{A}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Which means the above equation is invalid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Delta Method: Derivation of Asymtotic Sample Covariance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result is standard from asymtotic theory.
 Start with the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{XY}$
\end_inset

 and define 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{XY}\equiv\left[\left(X_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\mu_{Y}\right)\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
nS_{XY}= & \sum\left(X_{i}-\overline{X}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\overline{Y}\right)\\
nS_{XY}= & \sum\left(\left(X_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)-\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{X}\right)\right)\left(\left(Y_{i}-\mu_{Y}\right)-\left(\overline{Y}-\mu_{Y}\right)\right)\\
= & \sum\left(X_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\mu_{Y}\right)-\sum\left(X_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)\left(\overline{Y}-\mu_{Y}\right)\\
 & -\sum\left(Y_{i}-\mu_{Y}\right)\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{X}\right)+n\left(\overline{Y}-\mu_{Y}\right)\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{X}\right)\\
= & \sum\left(X_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\mu_{Y}\right)-n\left(\overline{Y}-\mu_{Y}\right)\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{X}\right)\\
n\left(S_{XY}-\sigma_{XY}\right)= & n\sum\frac{1}{n}\left[\left(X_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\mu_{Y}\right)-\sigma_{XY}\right]-n\left(\overline{Y}-\mu_{Y}\right)\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{X}\right)\\
\sqrt{n}\left(S_{XY}-\sigma_{XY}\right)= & \sqrt{n}\sum\frac{1}{n}\left[\left(X_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\mu_{Y}\right)-\sigma_{XY}\right]-\sqrt{n}\left(\overline{Y}-\mu_{Y}\right)\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{X}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now apply the asymtotics.
 By the Central Limit Theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{n}\left(\overline{Y}-\mu_{Y}\right)\stackrel{d}{\to}N\left(\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

.
 By the Weak Law of Large Numbers, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{X}\right)\stackrel{p}{\to}0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus by Slutsky's theorem, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{n}\left(\overline{Y}-\mu_{Y}\right)\left(\overline{X}-\mu_{X}\right)\to0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Applying the Central Limit Theorem to the remaining term implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{n}\left(S_{XY}-\sigma_{XY}\right)\stackrel{d}{\to}N\left(\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Note 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left[\sum\frac{1}{n}\left[\left(X_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\mu_{Y}\right)-\sigma_{XY}\right]\right]=0$
\end_inset

.
 The variance is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
V & \left[\left(X_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)\left(Y_{i}-\mu_{Y}\right)\right]=E\left[\left(X_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)^{2}\left(Y_{i}-\mu_{Y}\right)^{2}\right]-E\left[\left(X_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)^{2}\right]E\left[\left(Y_{i}-\mu_{Y}\right)^{2}\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{XXYY}\equiv E\left[\left(X_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)^{2}\left(Y_{i}-\mu_{Y}\right)^{2}\right]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{X}^{2}\equiv E\left[\left(X_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)^{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{Y}^{2}\equiv E\left[\left(Y_{i}-\mu_{Y}\right)^{2}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have shown:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{n}\left(S_{XY}-\sigma_{XY}\right)\stackrel{d}{\to} & N\left(0,\;\sigma_{XXYY}-\sigma_{X}^{2}\sigma_{Y}^{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a special case, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be drawn from the same distribution.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{X^{4}}\equiv E\left[\left(X_{i}-\mu_{X}\right)^{4}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{n}\left(S_{X}-\sigma_{X}^{2}\right)\stackrel{d}{\to} & N\left(0,\;\sigma_{X^{4}}-\sigma_{X}^{4}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Q.E.D.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
MCMC
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use a Bayesian MCMC approach, with Gibbs sampling
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This approach relies heavily on the central limit theorem and other asymptotics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Suppose we pick a test portfolio P of mx1 weights 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{P}$
\end_inset

 from which to test our candidate weights for the minimum variance portfolio
 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{G}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G}$
\end_inset

 as the sample variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{G}$
\end_inset

, the returns of all assets weighted by 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{G}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{GP}$
\end_inset

 as the sample covariance of the minimum variance portfolio and the test
 portfolio.
 For shorthand, designate 
\begin_inset Formula $S\equiv\left\{ S_{G},\,S_{GP}\right\} $
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Note given 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{G}$
\end_inset

, the test portfolio weights 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{P}$
\end_inset

, and the data 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is fully specified.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{P},\,D,\,w_{G}$
\end_inset

 only enter the model via 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, conditioning on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to conditioning on 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{P}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{G}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{G}^{2}\equiv\frac{\mu_{4G}-\sigma_{G}^{4}}{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{P}^{2}\equiv\frac{\mu_{4P}-\sigma_{P}^{4}}{n}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{GP}\equiv\frac{\sigma_{GGPP}-\sigma_{GP}^{2}}{n}$
\end_inset

 (all unobserved).
 For shorthand, designate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Z & \equiv\begin{bmatrix}\frac{\mu_{4G}-\sigma_{G}^{4}}{n} & \frac{\sigma_{GGPP}-\sigma_{GP}^{2}}{n}\\
\frac{\sigma_{GGPP}-\sigma_{GP}^{2}}{n} & \frac{\mu_{4P}-\sigma_{P}^{4}}{n}
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{bmatrix}\zeta_{G}^{2} & \zeta_{GP}\\
\zeta_{GP} & \zeta_{P}^{2}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Without imposing additional structure, we must estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{G}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{G}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, we will find it useful to draw 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G}$
\end_inset

 given the available data.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Unfortunately, directly evaluating the weights leads to intractable posteriors.
 This leads to the following general 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

almost MCMC
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 algorithm:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Draw a random test portfolio P with overall returns 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{P}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Draw from 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\sigma_{G}^{2}|\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(Z|\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(S_{G}|\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

 that is, draw from the parameter posteriors for these parameters given
 all other parameters.
 Note this fully specifies a new vector of weights for 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{G}$
\end_inset

, as shown in the following steps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now we partition the portfolio into three components.
 Assign each index 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in1:m$
\end_inset

 to one of sets 
\begin_inset Formula $G1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $G2$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $G3$
\end_inset

.
 Then define the following mx1 vectors:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Omega_{G1}\equiv & \omega_{G1}\left\{ \iota\left(i\in G1\right)\right\} _{i\in1:m}\\
\Omega_{G2}\equiv & \omega_{G2}\left\{ \iota\left(i\in G2\right)\right\} _{i\in1:m}\\
\Omega_{G3}\equiv & \omega_{G3}\left\{ \iota\left(i\in G3\right)\right\} _{i\in1:m}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota$
\end_inset

is an indicator function, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{G1},\,\omega_{G2},\,\omega_{G3}$
\end_inset

 are scalars.
 That is, each vector contains a constant value for all assigned indices
 and zero for all other indices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{G}'\equiv\left\{ \left(\Omega_{iG1}+\Omega_{iG2}+\Omega_{iG3}\right)w_{iG}\right\} _{i\in1:m}$
\end_inset

.
 Then solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\equiv\left\{ \omega_{G1},\,\omega_{G2},\,\omega_{G3}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Note that these parameters are fully specified by the following three condition
s:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The sample variance of the new vector of weights is 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(R_{G}'\right)=S_{G}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The sample covariance of the new vector of weights with the test portfolio
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{GP}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $cov\left(R_{G}',\,R_{P}\right)=S_{GP}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The weights of the new portfolio add to 1.
 This can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Omega_{G1}+\Omega_{G2}+\Omega_{G3}\right)\cdot w_{G}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Rotate the partition assignments by one unit and epeat steps 1-5
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Likelihood
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The likelihood is derived from a multivariate normal:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p\left(S|w_{G},\,Z,\,\sigma_{G}^{2},\,w_{P}\right)\propto & det\begin{bmatrix}\zeta_{G}^{2} & \zeta_{GP}\\
\zeta_{GP} & \zeta_{P}^{2}
\end{bmatrix}^{-\frac{1}{2}}\exp\left[-\left(\begin{bmatrix}S_{G}\\
S_{GP}
\end{bmatrix}-\begin{bmatrix}\sigma_{G}^{2}\\
\sigma_{G}^{2}
\end{bmatrix}\right)^{'}\begin{bmatrix}\zeta_{G}^{2} & \zeta_{GP}\\
\zeta_{GP} & \zeta_{P}^{2}
\end{bmatrix}^{-1}\left(\begin{bmatrix}S_{G}\\
S_{GP}
\end{bmatrix}-\begin{bmatrix}\sigma_{G}^{2}\\
\sigma_{G}^{2}
\end{bmatrix}\right)\right]\\
\propto & det\left[Z\right]^{-\frac{1}{2}}\exp\left[-\left(S-\sigma_{G}^{2}1\right)^{'}Z^{-1}\left(S-\sigma_{G}^{2}1\right)\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Priors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following conjugate priors allow for tractable posteriro distributions.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the matrix-valued Inverse Wishart distribution, while 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{+}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the normal distribution truncated at 0.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{G}^{2}\sim & N_{+}\left(\theta_{G},\,\delta_{G}^{2}\right)\\
S_{G}\sim & N_{+}\left(\theta_{SG},\,\delta_{SG}^{2}\right)\\
Z\sim & W^{-1}\left(\Psi,\;\nu\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the properties of the inverse Wishart, we must pick 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi=\begin{bmatrix}\psi_{G} & \psi_{GP}\\
\psi_{GP} & \psi_{P}
\end{bmatrix}$
\end_inset

, a symmetric positive semi-definite matrix, along with 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 Also note that the mean of an inverse Wishart distribution is given by
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\Psi}{\nu-3}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu>3$
\end_inset

.
 The hyperparameters for 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{-1}$
\end_inset

 are thereby selected as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The asymptotics rely on the existence of a mean to apply the CLT, which
 is equivalent to saying that the fourth moments required by the asymptotics
 exist.
 Beyond this assertion, we are highly uncertain of our priors, so pick 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=3.01$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{G}$
\end_inset

, as an extremely rough approximation, the volatility of the VIX ,using
 the CBOE's VVIX contract, on March 10, 2019 is around .87, corresponding
 to a 30-day variance of about .76.
 Divide by 20 to get the daily variance, and divide by 510 since we are
 averaging over 510 samples.
 Again, this is extremely rough, so multiply by 2 to account for our uncertainty.
 This leaves a prior for
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{G}$
\end_inset

 of about 1.5e-4.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{P}$
\end_inset

, use the same prior as 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{G}$
\end_inset

 but multiply by 2 to account for the additional uncertainty related to
 the portfolio sampling process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{SG}$
\end_inset

, note an error in the sample variance of G will mechanically affect the
 covariance by the square root of the variance error.
 As previously discussed, the point estimate for the variance error is about
 7.5e-5, with a square root of 0.0087.
 Multiplying by the point estimate of the variance of P yields an estimate
 for the covariance of 6.5e-7, with a correlation of .0087 (since both point
 estimates are the same).
 Divide by 2 to account for general uncertainty regarding the calculation,
 so 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{GP}$
\end_inset

=3e-7.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The normal distributions implicitly include the degenerate priors that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{G}^{2}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G}>0$
\end_inset

.
 This turns out to not affect the tractability of the posterior distributions.
 The remaining hyperparameters are selected as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use the current value of the VIX for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{G}$
\end_inset

.
 As of March 10, 2019 it was ~16%, which implies a variance of about 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{G}=.026$
\end_inset

.
 Divide by 20 to account for our use of daily data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{G}^{2}$
\end_inset

, start with the variance implied by VVIX of 0.76.
 Again, divide by 20 to make the estimate daily, then multiply by 2 to account
 for the uncertainty of our estimate.
 This yields variance of about 
\begin_inset Formula $0.15$
\end_inset

 to serve as our estimate for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{G}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 As we are picking 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{2}$
\end_inset

 based on the uncertainty of our prior, we do not divide by 510.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For the sample estimates, assume that they have the same properties of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{G}^{2}$
\end_inset

 except that they are measured with noise.
 We therefore impose the same value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{SG}$
\end_inset

 and multiply the variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{SG}^{2}$
\end_inset

 by 2 to account for the additional noise.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, results which were overly sensitive to the priors would call the
 conclusions into question.
 Therefore, check the sensitivity of the approach by using a second set
 of less informative priors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We still rely on the existence of a mean, so for Z we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=3.01$
\end_inset

.
 For the other hyperparameters, set 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{G}=\psi_{P}=1.0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{GP}=0.0$
\end_inset

.
 Set all other hyper-parameters to 
\begin_inset Formula $1.0$
\end_inset

 and retain the truncation of the normal distributions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Posteriors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Start with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{G}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Use the property that the convolution of normals is a normal 
\begin_inset Formula $N\left(a,b\right)$
\end_inset

 where a is the precision weighted average of the source means and b is
 the inverse sum of the source precisions.
 As an intermediate step, we must complete the square in order to express
 the function in the correct form.
 This requires lots of tedious algebra and hence is completed in Mathematica.
 See the file 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Algebra Posteriors
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the specific details.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p\left(S_{GP}|Z,\,\sigma_{G}^{2},\,S_{G}\right)\propto & det\begin{bmatrix}\zeta_{G}^{2} & \zeta_{GP}\\
\zeta_{GP} & \zeta_{P}^{2}
\end{bmatrix}^{-\frac{1}{2}}\exp\left[-\frac{1}{2}\left(\begin{bmatrix}S_{G}\\
S_{GP}
\end{bmatrix}-\begin{bmatrix}\sigma_{G}^{2}\\
\sigma_{G}^{2}
\end{bmatrix}\right)^{'}\begin{bmatrix}\zeta_{G}^{2} & \zeta_{GP}\\
\zeta_{GP} & \zeta_{P}^{2}
\end{bmatrix}^{-1}\left(\begin{bmatrix}S_{G}\\
S_{GP}
\end{bmatrix}-\begin{bmatrix}\sigma_{G}^{2}\\
\sigma_{G}^{2}
\end{bmatrix}\right)\right]\\
\propto & \exp\left[-\frac{1}{2}\left(\begin{bmatrix}S_{G}\\
S_{GP}
\end{bmatrix}-\begin{bmatrix}\sigma_{G}^{2}\\
\sigma_{G}^{2}
\end{bmatrix}\right)^{'}\begin{bmatrix}\zeta_{G}^{2} & \zeta_{GP}\\
\zeta_{GP} & \zeta_{P}^{2}
\end{bmatrix}^{-1}\left(\begin{bmatrix}S_{G}\\
S_{GP}
\end{bmatrix}-\begin{bmatrix}\sigma_{G}^{2}\\
\sigma_{G}^{2}
\end{bmatrix}\right)\right]\\
\propto & \frac{-\left(\frac{(S_{G}(\zeta_{G}-2\zeta_{GP}+\zeta_{P}^{2})+S_{G}(\zeta_{GP}-\zeta_{P}^{2})}{(\zeta_{GP}-\zeta_{G}^{2})}+\sigma_{G}^{2}\right)^{2}}{2\frac{(\zeta_{G}^{2}-2\zeta_{GP}+\zeta_{P}^{2})\left(\zeta_{G}^{2}\zeta_{P}^{2}-\zeta_{GP}^{2}\right)}{\left(\zeta_{GP}-\zeta_{G}^{2}\right)^{2}}}\\
\propto & N\left(\mu_{G},\,\gamma_{G}^{2}\right)\\
\mu_{G}\equiv & -\frac{(S_{G}(\zeta_{G}-2\zeta_{GP}+\zeta_{P}^{2})+S_{G}(\zeta_{GP}-\zeta_{P}^{2})}{(\zeta_{GP}-\zeta_{G}^{2})}\\
\gamma_{G}^{2}= & \frac{(\zeta_{G}^{2}-2\zeta_{GP}+\zeta_{P}^{2})\left(\zeta_{G}^{2}\zeta_{P}^{2}-\zeta_{GP}^{2}\right)}{\left(\zeta_{GP}-\zeta_{G}^{2}\right)^{2}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now convolute the truncated normal prior by the above normal distribution
 to obtain the posteriors:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p\left(\sigma_{G}^{2}|S,\,\zeta^{2}\right)\propto & p\left(S_{GP}|Z,\,\sigma_{G}^{2},\,S_{G}\right)p\left(\sigma_{G}^{2};\,N_{T}\left(\theta_{G},\,\delta_{G}^{2}\right)\right)\\
\propto & \frac{1}{\gamma}\exp\left[-\frac{\left(\sigma_{G}^{2}-\mu_{G}\right)}{\gamma_{G}^{2}}\right]\times\left(\frac{1}{\delta_{G}^{2}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}\exp\left[-\frac{\left(\theta_{G}-\sigma_{G}^{2}\right)^{2}}{2\delta_{G}^{2}}\right]\times\frac{\iota\left(\sigma_{G}^{2}>0\right)}{1-\Phi\left(\frac{-\theta_{G}}{\delta_{G}^{2}}\right)}\\
\propto & \exp\left[-\frac{\left(\sigma_{G}^{2}-\mu_{G}\right)}{\gamma_{G}^{2}}\right]\exp\left[-\frac{\left(\theta_{G}-\sigma_{G}^{2}\right)^{2}}{2\delta_{G}^{2}}\right]\times\iota\left(\sigma_{G}^{2}>0\right)\\
\\
\propto & p\left(\sigma_{G}^{2},\,N\left(\left[\frac{\mu_{G}}{\gamma_{G}^{2}}+\frac{\theta_{G}}{\delta_{G}^{2}}\right]\zeta_{G}^{2*},\;\zeta_{G}^{2*}\right)\iota\left(\sigma_{G}^{2}>0\right)\right)\\
s.t.\\
\zeta_{G}^{2*}= & \left[\frac{1}{\gamma_{G}^{2}}+\frac{1}{\delta_{G}^{2}}\right]^{-1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note the truncated part of the distribution is a constant, and does not
 affect the marginal distribution beyond the indicator function, at least
 up to the constant of proportionality
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Now for 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
First define:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Sigma\equiv & \begin{bmatrix}\left(S_{G}-\sigma_{G}^{2}\right)^{2} & \left(S_{G}-\sigma_{G}^{2}\right)\left(S_{GP}-\sigma_{G}^{2}\right)\\
\left(S_{G}-\sigma_{G}^{2}\right)\left(S_{GP}-\sigma_{G}^{2}\right) & \left(S_{GP}-\sigma_{G}^{2}\right)^{2}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Then just plug into the standard formula for the posterior distribution
 of an Inverse Wishart distribution: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p\left(\zeta_{G}^{2}|S,\,\zeta_{P}^{2}\,\sigma_{G}^{2}\right)\propto & p\left(S_{GP}|Z,\,\sigma_{G}^{2},\,S_{G}\right)p\left(Z;\;W^{-1}\left(\nu,\,\Psi\right)\right)\\
\propto & p\left(\nu+1,\,\Psi+\Sigma\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G}$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Start by deriving the distribution of a conditional normal distribution.
 Use the the bivariate normal's property of having a conditional distribution
 which is also normal (like a regression).
 Plugging in:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu_{SG}\equiv & \sigma_{G}^{2}+\frac{\zeta_{GP}}{\zeta_{P}^{2}}\left(SGP-\sigma_{G}^{2}\right)\\
\gamma_{SG}^{2}\equiv & \zeta_{G}^{2}-\frac{\zeta_{GP}^{2}}{\zeta_{P}^{2}}\\
p\left(S_{GP}|Z,\,\sigma_{G}^{2},\,S_{G}\right)\propto & N\left(\mu_{SG},\,\gamma_{SG}^{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now convolute the conditional distribution with the prior to get the posterior
 (truncating the normal as before):
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p\left(S_{G}|Z,\,\sigma_{G}^{2},\,S_{GP}\right)\propto & p\left(S_{GP}|Z,\,\sigma_{G}^{2},\,S\right)p\left(S_{G};\,N\left(\theta_{SG},\,\delta_{SG}^{2}\right)\right)\\
\propto & \left(\frac{1}{\gamma_{SG}^{2}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}\exp\left[-\frac{\left(S_{G}-\mu_{SG}\right)^{2}}{2\gamma_{SG}^{2}}\right]\times\left(\frac{1}{\delta_{SG}^{2}}\right)^{\frac{1}{2}}\exp\left[-\frac{\left(\theta_{SG}-S_{G}\right)^{2}}{2\delta_{SG}^{2}}\right]\times\frac{\iota\left(S_{SG}>0\right)}{1-\Phi\left(\frac{-\theta_{SG}}{\delta_{SG}^{2}}\right)}\\
\propto & p\left(\sigma_{G}^{2},\,N\left(\left[\frac{\sigma_{G}^{2}}{\gamma_{SG}^{2}}+\frac{\theta_{SG}}{\delta_{SG}^{2}}\right]\zeta_{SG}^{2*},\;\zeta_{SG}^{2*}\right)\iota\left(S_{SG}>0\right)\right)\\
s.t.\\
\zeta_{SG}^{2*}= & \left[\frac{1}{\gamma_{SG}^{2}}+\frac{1}{\delta_{SG}^{2}}\right]^{-1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Mapping draws to weights
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denote the three partitions of G as
\begin_inset Formula $G1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $G2$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $G3$
\end_inset

, each of which has weight vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{Gk}\in\mathbb{R}^{M}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\left\{ 1,2,3\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Note that for each k, the weights for indices not in the partition are
 equal to 0.
 These definitions imply 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{G}'\equiv\left\{ \left(\Omega_{iG1}+\Omega_{iG2}+\Omega_{iG3}\right)w_{iG}\right\} _{i\in1:m}$
\end_inset

.
 Next, denote the scaling vector
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\in\mathbb{R}^{3}\equiv\left\{ \omega_{G1},\,\omega_{G2},\,\omega_{G3}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Note that these parameters are fully specified by the following three restricti
ons:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The sample variance of the new vector of weights is 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(R_{G}'\right)=S_{G}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The sample covariance of the new vector of weights with the test portfolio
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{GP}$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $cov\left(R_{G}',\,R_{P}\right)=S_{GP}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The weights of the new portfolio add to 1.
 This can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Omega_{G1}+\Omega_{G2}+\Omega_{G3}\right)\cdot w_{G}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve for the scaling parameters, make the following three definitions.
 Note that each of these quantities is known given the previous value of
 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{G}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
w_{s}= & \left\{ \sum_{i\in1:m}w_{iG}\iota\left(i\in Gk\right)\right\} _{k\in1:3}\text{ (3x1)}\\
Q_{G}= & \begin{bmatrix}S_{G1} & S_{G12} & S_{G13}\\
S_{G12} & S_{G2} & S_{G23}\\
S_{G13} & S_{G23} & S_{G3}
\end{bmatrix}\text{ (3x3)}\\
Q_{PG}= & \begin{bmatrix}S_{PG1}\\
S_{PG2}\\
S_{PG3}
\end{bmatrix}\text{ (3x1)}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G1}\in\mathbb{R}_{+}$
\end_inset

 is the sample variance of the G1 partition, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G13}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is the sample covariance between the G1 and G3 portfolios, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{PG1}$
\end_inset

is the covariance between portfolio P and the G1 portfolio, and other variances
 and covariances are analogous.
 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{s}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is the sum of the weights of the G1, G2, and G3 portfolio partitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then solve:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S_{G} & =\omega'Q_{G}\omega\\
S_{GP} & =\omega'Q_{PG}\\
1 & =\omega'1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which correspond to the three restrictions.
 The algorithm does NOT obtain the solution by treating the above as a quadratic
 programming problem.
 Instead, it uses precise analytical solutions.
 The specific algebra is tedious and long, and the resulting equations impart
 little intuition.
 The solution is thus relegated to the code appendix and the algebra to
 the Mathematica file 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Weights Algebra.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Alternative Algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This follows the same approach, except without the partitions.
 So we sacrifice a closed form but we get some standardization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use a Bayesian MCMC approach, with Gibbs sampling
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Suppose we pick M-2 test portfolios, each of which has weights mx1 weights
 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{P}^{k}\in\Re^{M}$
\end_inset

 (for portfolio m) from which to test our candidate weights for the minimum
 variance portfolio 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{G}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G}$
\end_inset

 as the sample variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{G}$
\end_inset

, the returns of all assets weighted by 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{G}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{GP}^{k}$
\end_inset

 as the sample covariance of the minimum variance portfolio and and test
 portfolio m.
 For shorthand, designate 
\begin_inset Formula $S\equiv\left\{ S_{G},\,S_{GP}^{1}....S_{GP}^{M-2}\right\} $
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Note given 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{G}$
\end_inset

, the test portfolio weights 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{P}^{1}...w_{P}^{M-2}$
\end_inset

, and the data 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is fully specified.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{P},\,D,\,w_{G}$
\end_inset

 only enter the model via 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, conditioning on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to conditioning on 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{P}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{G}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{G}^{2}\equiv\frac{\mu_{4G}-\sigma_{G}^{4}}{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{P}^{2}\equiv\frac{\mu_{4P}-\sigma_{P}^{4}}{n}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{GP}\equiv\frac{\sigma_{GGPP}-\sigma_{GP}^{2}}{n}$
\end_inset

 (all unobserved).
 For shorthand, designate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Z & \equiv\begin{bmatrix}\frac{\mu_{4G}-\sigma_{G}^{4}}{n} & \frac{\sigma_{GGPP}-\sigma_{GP}^{2}}{n}\\
\frac{\sigma_{GGPP}-\sigma_{GP}^{2}}{n} & \frac{\mu_{4P}-\sigma_{P}^{4}}{n}
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{bmatrix}\zeta_{G}^{2} & \zeta_{GP}\\
\zeta_{GP} & \zeta_{P}^{2}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Without imposing additional structure, we must estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{G}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{G}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, we will find it useful to draw 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G}$
\end_inset

 given the available data.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We can directly evaluate the posterios as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Draw M-2 random portfolios, each of which have a total weight of 1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Draw from 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\sigma_{G}^{2}|\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(Z|\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(S_{G}|\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

 that is, draw from the parameter posteriors for these parameters given
 all other parameters.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Draw 
\begin_inset Formula $M-2$
\end_inset

 picks of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{GP}^{M}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute the implied weigts.
 The weights are fully specified (see mapping to implied weights
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Repeat all steps many many times
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Mapping to implied weights
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We fully specify the minimum variance portfolio given the following restrictions
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The sample variance of the new vector of weights is 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{G}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(R_{G}'\right)=S_{G}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The sample covariance of test portfolio k is 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{GP}^{k}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The weights of the new portfolio add to 1.
 This can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $1'w_{G}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus we just solve for the weights implied by these restrictions, summarized
 as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S_{G}= & \frac{1}{N}\sum_{1}^{N}\left(z'w_{G}-\overline{z}'w_{G}\right)^{2}\\
S_{GP}^{k}= & \frac{1}{N}\sum_{1}^{N}\left(z'w_{G}-\overline{z}'w_{G}\right)\left(z'w_{P}^{k}-\overline{z}'w_{P}^{k}\right)\\
1'w_{G}= & 1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can be written as a quartic optimization problem with M parameters:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & \min_{w_{G}\in\mathbb{R}^{M}}\left[\frac{1}{N}\sum_{1}^{N}\left(z'w_{G}-\overline{z}'w_{G}\right)^{2}-S_{G}\right]^{2}+\left[\frac{1}{N}\sum_{1}^{N}\left(z'w_{G}-\overline{z}'w_{G}\right)\left(z'w_{P}^{k}-\overline{z}'w_{P}^{k}\right)-S_{GP}^{k}\right]^{2}+\left[1'w_{G}-1\right]^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

